&quot;cd -&quot; and also using &quot;cd&quot; with no arguments to get back to $HOME are great tips. I also have a bash function called &quot;up&quot; to get back N directories up the hierarchy so I can do &quot;up 5&quot; which is like &quot;cd ../../../../..&quot; but much easier to type.<p><pre><code>    up () {
        if [[ $# -eq 1 && &quot;$1&quot; -gt 0 ]] ; then
            local i d
            for (( i = 0; i < $1; i++ )) ; do d=&quot;../$d&quot; ; done
            cd $d
        else
            echo &quot;Usage: up N&quot;
        fi
    }</code></pre>
